onary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (northeastern Scotland and Shetland): shortened form of   Chaney  , of Norman origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Chaney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any one of several places in Normandy, Picardy, or Artois (France) named (Le) Quesnay or Quesnoy, or elsewhere in northern France named (Le or La) Chesnay or Chesnoy. The placenames all derive from Old French <i>chesnai</i> or its Normanno-Picard equivalent <i>quesnai</i> ‘oak grove’ (medieval Latin <i>casnetum</i>).","French: variant of <b>Chanet</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Chanet or Le Chanet, from Latin <i>canna</i> ‘reed’ + the suffix <i>-etum</i> denoting an inhabitant."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Freskin Francis Cheyne was born about 1260, in Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland, his father, Reginald le Chen, was 27 and his mother, Mary de Moray, was 22. He married Isabel Comyn about 1290, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1345, in Inverness-shire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 86, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"about 1260–1345":"umbes 1260–1345","1255–1328":"1255–1328","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1262–Female":"1262–Surnud","1270–1345":"1270–1345","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301–Surnud","1235–1312":"1235–1312","1240–1271":"1240–1271","about 1260":"umbes 1260","6 November 1312":"6. november 1312","about 1292":"umbes 1292","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","1271":"1271","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1335":"1335","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","Abt 1341":"umbes 1341","about 1255":"umbes 1255","1328":"1328","As Sheriff of, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perth, Perthshire, , Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland":"Straloch, Perthshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1260–1345":"noin 1260–1345","1255–1328":"1255–1328","1260–1345":"1260–1345","1262–Female":"1262–Kuollut","1270–1345":"1270–1345","1275–1335":"1275–1335","1292–1341":"1292–1341","1301–Male":"1301–Kuollut","1235–1312":"1235–1312","1240–1271":"1240–1271","about 1260":"noin 1260","6 November 1312":"6. marraskuuta 1312","about 1292":"noin 1292","about 1290":"noin 1290","1341":"1341","1275":"1275","1240":"1240","1262":"1262","1271":"1271","1260":"1260","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1335":"1335","1301":"1301","1345":"1345","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","1255":"1255","Abt 1341":"noin 1341","about 1255":"noin 1255","1328":"1328","As Sheriff of, Inverness-shire, Scotland":"Inverness-shire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Perth, Perthshire, , Scotland":"Perth, Perthshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Stral